Month.Additional Comments: The peak of the peak season with school summer holidays in full swing, taking advantage of the long, hot days. On average this is the hottest month.

Almost as hot as January, but the kids are back at school, so the beaches are less crowded. From mid-February the Mardi Gras influx starts to arrive. Sydney has an excellent Chinatown and a strong Chinese population so you can't miss the colors of Chinese New Year parades either.   
Key events: Chinese New Year, Tropfest

March kicks off with the Sydney Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras parade, a spectacle that everyone in Sydney loves to watch whether they're part of the queer community or not. Temperatures are still balmy, but it's traditionally Sydney's wettest month so pack an umbrella or a raincoat in your daypack. 
Key events: Sydney Gay and Lesbian Mardis Gras, Taste of Sydney

As autumn progresses, showers are more frequent, but it's never particularly cold. Locals make the most of the long Easter weekend which coincides with a two-week school holidays period creating a second mini-peak season in Sydney. Children love the Royal Easter Show, but parents may want to set a budget before you arrive.
Key events: Royal Easter Show, Sydney Autumn Racing Carnival, Sydney Comedy Festival

Average daily temperature high finally dip below 20C and rainfall can put a stop to many outdoor plans, but Sydneysiders take it as an opportunity to lean into their arts and literary side.
Key events: Biennale of Sydney, Fashion Week, Vivid Sydney, Sydney Writers Festival

Sunshine hours shrink to their lowest levels as winter kicks in. The rugby league season keeps passions running hot.
Key events: State of Origin Series, Sydney Film Festival

The kids escape from school for the first two weeks of Sydney's coldest month, where the daily highs rarely strike above the mid-teens and the lows are in single figures, just Bring a warm coat but gloves, scarves and hats shouldn't be necessary. 
Key events: NAIDOC Week, Yulefest Blue Mountains

August is chilly but dry  perfect for a run to the beach, but only the most hardy types are tempted to get in for some cold water swimming.
Key events: Bledisloe Cup, City2Surf Run

Spring brings warming weather and sunny days. September is traditionally Sydney's driest month and daily highs scrape back above 20C. This is peak pre-summer fitness time in Sydney. Expect to see groups running, cycling and parkouring around the city.  
Key events: Sydney Design Week, Festival of the Winds, Sydney Running Festival

The pleasant spring weather continues. Workers get the Labour Day long weekend to enjoy it, while school students get the whole first week off. Once again major sites might be busier during school holidays.
Key events: National Rugby League Grand Final, Manly Jazz Festival, Good Food Month

November is a great time to visit Sydney. It's usually the sunniest month, averaging nearly eight hours of rays per day, with temperatures warm but rarely scorching.
Key events: Sculpture by the Sea, Graphic, Newtown Festival

Hello summer! Decembers in Sydney are hot and dry, and for the first three weeks the beaches are not too crowded before the school holidays unleash the masses. From Christmas onward things go crazy.
Key events: Bondi Christmas Bash, Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race, New Years Eve

Often scorching, January's temperatures regularly push into the 40s for a few days in a row  but they can sometimes drop below 20C for a few days too. It's school-holiday time, so beaches are crowded. Australia Day, a national public holiday, brings additional activity at the end of the month, as does the Australian Open, where the world's greatest tennis players brave the summertime heat. St Jerome's Laneway Festival, one of Melbournes biggest music events, also falls in January, making this a busy time to be in the city.
Key events: Australia Day; Australian Open; St Jerome's Laneway Festival

Another extremely hot month, but the kids are back at school, so you'll have more room at the beach. Nights can be uncomfortably warm and, although it's usually dry, there may be the odd thunderstorm. The lunar new year goes off with a bang in Chinatown as it's done for over 150 years, with dragons of the costumed variety roaming the streets. The date shifts between January and February.
Key events: Chinese New Year

Temperatures can still be unpleasantly hot at the beginning of the month but tend to cool down towards the end. Nights are noticeably cooler and it's generally fairly dry, excluding a few heavy downpours. Excitement levels ramp up a few gears for racing enthusiasts in March, as the Australian Formula One Grand Prix comes to town.
Key events: Australian Formula One Grand Prix

A particularly pleasant month, with warm days and cooler nights, though you might endure a couple of foggy mornings and strong winds. Rainfall is usually moderate but, this being Melbourne, that can't be guaranteed. Festivals, of both the comedic and food and wine variety, take place in April.
Key events: Melbourne International Comedy Festival; Melbourne Food & Wine Festival

Things cool down in May, with occasional overnight frosts towards the end of the month. Frost and fog generally give way to sunny days, but you'll probably strike some overcast and showery ones as well, with winter just around the corner. Good Beer Week, in May, celebrates all things ale, providing a good excuse to knock back local, interstate and international brews with like-minded obsessives at venues all over Melbourne.
Key events: Good Beer Week

Winter kicks in, with cold weather (well below 20C, and as low as 2C at night), sporadic frosts, plenty of fog and cloudy skies. Drizzle dampens spirits but rarely descends into heavy rain. Thankfully, June also plays host to the Melbourne International Jazz Festival, providing toe-tapping melodies to wipe away any encroaching winter blues.
Key events: Melbourne International Jazz Festival

July usually contains the year's coldest day, and plenty of layers of clothing are required to combat the icy winds. Fog descends and sometimes doesn't bother leaving, although it's usually gone by mid-morning. This is peak low season and tourist hotspots are quiet.
August is often the wettest month, although rain tends to fall more as drizzle and light showers than as heavy downpours. It's still cold, but a few days may creep above 20C.

Spring brings changeable weather, even by Melbourne standards. Be prepared for any combination of wet, dry, cold, warm, windy and calm  even in the same day! Considered by many as Australias biggest sporting event, the AFL Grand Final takes place in the city on the last Saturday in September, a game that carries the hopes and dreams of Melbourne's Aussie Rules footy fans  expect a fervent atmosphere.
Key events: AFL Grand Final

As changeable as September, October comes with even more variance in temperature: daily highs are just as likely to be below 15C as they are to be above 25C. There's a fair smattering of rain too. Fortunately, moods are easily buoyed by the Melbourne Festival, which sees the city's myriad stages and galleries filled with all manner of performances and exhibitions.
Key events: Melbourne Festival

Hot, cold, wet, dry  and completely unpredictable. Some November days swelter in the mid-30s, while others languish below 16C. Wild storms sometimes strike. The highlight of the month is undoubtedly the Melbourne Cup, one of the world's most famous horse races and the high point of Victorias Spring Racing Carnival. Everyone gets the day off and a party atmosphere prevails.
Key events: Melbourne Cup

Not as temperamental as November but still changeable weather. Hot day sometimes end in thunderstorms and sudden cool changes. Christmas, and all its accompanying festivities (and decorations) adds a crescendo to the month, followed by the annual Boxing Day cricket match at Melbourne Cricket Ground. The month ends in a bang, with half a million dollars' worth of fireworks lighting up the citys skyline on New Years Eve.
Key events: Christmas; Boxing Day Test; New Years Eve
